Hi,

We have found a bug in Tau-P C function bullen_radial_slowness_inner_loop from inner_tau_loops.c when obspy is compiled on IBM architectures. 

Sometimes, the function returns NaN values. This happens when square roots arguments: 
sqrt_top = sqrt(pow(LAYER(i, SL_TOP_P), 2) - pow(p[i], 2));
sqrt_bot = sqrt(pow(LAYER(i, SL_BOT_P), 2) - pow(p[i], 2));
are closed to zero.

In floating point arithmetic the argument may become slightly negative in which case some compilers return NaN while others return zero since sqrt_top and sqrt_bot are floats and not complex values. A workaround here is to take:
sqrt_top = sqrt(fmax(0.,pow(LAYER(i, SL_TOP_P), 2) - pow(p[i], 2)));
sqrt_bot = sqrt(fmax(0.,pow(LAYER(i, SL_BOT_P), 2) - pow(p[i], 2)));
fmax could probably be replaced with fabs, but I feel this is safer to use fmax.

Also, this check may not give the expected behavior:
if ((LAYER(i, SL_BOT_DEPTH) - LAYER(i, SL_TOP_DEPTH)) < 0.0000000001) {
    continue;
 }
if it happens that LAYER(i,j) presents a NaN value the condition will return false and later calculations will be performed with NaN values. It would be safer to add a second check for NaNs. Something like that:
double dumb_var = ((LAYER(i, SL_BOT_DEPTH) - LAYER(i, SL_TOP_DEPTH)) ;
if (dumb_var < 0.0000000001)  || isnan(dumb_var)) {continue;}
or the equivalent
if (dumb_var < 0.0000000001)  || dumb_var != dumb_var) {continue;}

Stephen

